article.headline: Mississippi 64, SE Louisiana 48
article.story: OXFORD, Miss. (AP) -- Londrick Nolen and Todd Abernethy each scored 13 points and Mississippi won its seventh straight game, defeating Southeastern Louisiana 64-48 on Friday afternoon. Abernethy broke out of a mini-slump, scoring 11 consecutive points with three straight 3-pointers to spark a game-clinching 14-2 run during the final eight minutes for the Rebels (9-4). Rickey Woods had 18 points and Terry Bryant had 16 for Southeastern Louisiana (7-5), which shot 56 percent (15-of-27) from the field but couldn't overcome 22 turnovers and a 34-20 rebounding disadvantage. The Rebels led 28-21 at halftime after a 13-3 run midway through the half was keyed by Nolen's 8 points. Southeastern Louisiana cut it to 42-39 with 8:06 remaining when Woods' layup capped a 9-0 run. But behind Abernethy's suddenly hot hand, the Rebels took command down the stretch. Abernethy was 1-of-7 from the field before leading the game-deciding run. Ole Miss finished 21-of-54 (39 percent) from the field. It was a sloppy way for both teams to end 2004; the game featured a total 49 personal fouls.
